{
  "slug": "the-robert-duvall-hall-of-fame",
  "title": "The Robert Duvall Hall of Fame",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Tracy Letts"
  ],
  "published": "2026-05-11",
  "runtimeMin": 163,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and playwright Tracy Letts spend two and a half hours walking Robert Duvall's entire filmography after his death at 95, sorting every part green, yellow, or red until ten films make the Hall of Fame. The Godfather I and II count as one slot; Lonesome Dove gets in despite being television. Each host also takes a 'blue' pick, a favorite from outside the ten.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "halloffame",
      "heading": "The Hall of Fame",
      "honoree": "Robert Duvall",
      "note": "the ten inducted films, plus each host's blue pick",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "To Kill a Mockingbird",
          "year": 1962,
          "role": "Boo Radley",
          "note": "His film debut, cast on Horton Foote's recommendation. No lines, and he doesn't appear until the end, but Letts calls Boo Radley deceptively hard: 'You have to convey a lot in a short amount of time with no lines.' White pallor, shock of white hair, haunted. 'He looks like a ghost,' and he never looked that way again."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Godfather",
          "year": 1972,
          "role": "Tom Hagen",
          "note": "One slot for Parts I and II (Part III inducted honorarily for Duvall's absence, which Letts calls 'pure director hubris'). Sean's emotional entry point as the taciturn adopted consigliere. Letts: for an actor who could be so explosive, choosing to withdraw against Vito, Sonny and Michael is 'very shrewd. He's really the metronome of the movie.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Tomorrow",
          "year": 1972,
          "role": "Jackson Fentry",
          "note": "A near-total discovery for both, and Duvall's own favorite of his films. Horton Foote adapting Faulkner; Duvall as a poor migrant farmer who bonds with a pregnant woman. A big-swing accent that Billy Bob Thornton later lifted for Sling Blade. Sean: 'a great movie, a great performance,' and it followed The Godfather that same year."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Outfit",
          "year": 1973,
          "role": "Earl Macklin",
          "note": "John Flynn's down-and-dirty Parker adaptation (Macklin is Parker), with a Walter Hill polish. 'I was knocked out by The Outfit.' A tough-guy movie-star part on a revenge tour, cast Karen Black, Joe Don Baker, Robert Ryan, Timothy Carey. Yellow that Sean pushed to green."
        },
        {
          "title": "Network",
          "year": 1976,
          "role": "Frank Hackett",
          "note": "Instant green. The corporate hatchet man, and one of Sean's single favorite performances in movie history. The 'Ruddy doesn't count anymore' scene: 'his glee and rage and energy and bewilderment.' Letts on the Chayefsky dialogue: 'he fucking eats that scene up.' Note the paper acting."
        },
        {
          "title": "Apocalypse Now",
          "year": 1979,
          "role": "Lt. Col. Bill Kilgore",
          "note": "Green for a scene and a half. The surfing, the neckerchief, 'someday this war is going to end,' then he walks off screen. 'The delusional rock-and-roll energy,' a grand, theatrical style he rarely used. Duvall always resented the cut; Letts doesn't read it that way at all."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Great Santini",
          "year": 1979,
          "role": "Bull Meechum",
          "note": "'Anybody who's ever had a father relates to this movie.' A domineering Marine dad who is also loving, which is why Blythe Danner and Michael O'Keefe playing against him matters. Letts, who had a domineering father: 'very real shit.' In the lexicon for what tough dads do."
        },
        {
          "title": "Tender Mercies",
          "year": 1983,
          "role": "Mac Sledge",
          "note": "His only Oscar, Best Actor, as a washed-up country singer on the downside of his life. One of his quietest, most sensitive performances, and one of the two or three films you'd show to explain him. Duvall insisted on singing the songs himself. Sean would swap it for Terms of Endearment as Best Picture."
        },
        {
          "title": "Lonesome Dove",
          "year": 1989,
          "role": "Gus McCrae",
          "note": "In despite being television, on the Big Little Lies precedent. Letts: 'the greatest miniseries in the history of television,' and Duvall 'elevates the art form of television acting.' His final scene is 'one of the great scenes in the history of television,' bizarrely real if you've been with someone near the end."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Apostle",
          "year": 1997,
          "role": "Sonny Dewey",
          "note": "A decades-long passion project he wrote, directed, produced and self-financed, first drafted in 1983. A preacher who does something terrible, vanishes, and launches a new church as 'the Apostle E.F.' Oscar-nominated. 'A really fascinating and clearly very personal story about good people doing bad things.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "THX 1138",
          "year": 1971,
          "role": "THX 1138",
          "note": "Sean's blue pick, outside the ten. George Lucas's debut and his first leading film role, internal and measured, from the Walter Murch soundscape to the Synanon-cult extras. Letts calls it Lucas's best film. Duvall met Lucas when Lucas was filming a documentary about The Rain People."
        },
        {
          "title": "Open Range",
          "year": 2003,
          "role": "Boss Spearman",
          "note": "Tracy's blue pick, outside the ten. 'What an ass kicker.' Costner directs and stars; the final 40 minutes is a long, well-staged Western gunfight. Duvall as the older hand steadying the younger one. He hurt himself falling off a horse making it, and rode less afterward."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
